---
export const prerender = true;
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
---

<BlogLayout
  title="Three-Letter Words With Z in Scrabble"
  description="All valid 3-letter Z words in Scrabble: ZAP, ZAX, ZEP, ZIT, ZOO, AZO, ADZ, BIZ, FEZ and more. Z placement strategy for premium squares. Free guide. Free."
  keywords="three letter words with z, 3 letter z words, z scrabble words, highest z words, z words for scrabble, short z words"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Three-Letter Words With Z in Scrabble",
    "description": "All valid 3-letter Z words in Scrabble: ZAP, ZAX, ZEP, ZIT, ZOO, AZO, ADZ, BIZ, FEZ and more. Z placement strategy for premium squares.",
    "datePublished": "2026-06-14",
    "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com" },
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/blog/three-letter-words-with-z" }
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are the best 3-letter Z words in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "ZAX (19 points) is the highest-scoring 3-letter Z word. Other top choices include ZEK (16), FEZ (15), WIZ (15), ZEP (14), ZAP (14), BIZ (14), and COZ (14). Z words dominate the highest-scoring 3-letter word rankings because Z is worth 10 points per tile." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How many valid 3-letter words contain Z in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "There are over 20 valid 3-letter words containing Z in the official Scrabble dictionaries. These include words with Z at the beginning (ZAP, ZAX, ZAG, ZEP, ZIT, ZIG, ZOO), middle (AZO), and end (ADZ, BIZ, COZ, FEZ, WIZ). Learning all of them gives you maximum flexibility when you draw the Z tile." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Where should I place the Z tile for maximum points?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Place Z on a Triple Letter Score (TLS) whenever possible — it makes Z worth 30 points for that tile alone. On a Double Letter Score, Z becomes 20 points. If you can get the entire Z word on a Triple Word Score square, the whole word is tripled. ZAX on TWS = 57 points." }
      }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <article class="prose prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <span class="text-gray-300">Three-Letter Words</span>
      </nav>

      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Three-Letter Words With Z in Scrabble</h1>

      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-14">June 14, 2026</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>5 min read</span>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔍</span> Solver</a> <a href="/activities/#quiz" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🎯</span> Quiz</a> <a href="/activities/#anagram" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔀</span> Anagram</a> <a href="/activities/#rack" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🎲</span> Rack</a> <a href="/activities/#wotd" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">📖</span> WOTD</a> <a href="/sixty-seconds/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">⏱️</span> 60s</a>
      </div>

      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-300 mb-8">
        Z is the joint-highest-value tile in Scrabble at 10 points, and unlike Q, it pairs beautifully with common letters. This makes 3-letter Z words some of the most powerful short plays in the game. Whether Z sits at the beginning, middle, or end of the word, you've got options — and every one of them scores well. Here's the complete guide to mastering Z in 3-letter words.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Complete List: All 3-Letter Z Words</h2>
      <p>Every word below is valid in official Scrabble dictionaries (TWL and SOWPODS). They're grouped by Z position for easy memorisation.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-medium text-gray-200 mt-6 mb-3">Z at the Beginning</h3>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose my-4">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <thead class="bg-gray-800">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Word</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Points</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Meaning</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-800">
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">ZAX</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">19</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">A tool for cutting roofing slates</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">ZEK</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">16</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">A prisoner in a Soviet labour camp</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">ZEP</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">14</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Short for zeppelin</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">ZAP</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">14</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">To destroy or strike suddenly</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">ZAG</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">13</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">A sharp change of direction</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">ZIG</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">13</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">To make a sharp turn</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">ZED</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">13</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">The letter Z (British pronunciation)</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">ZIT</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">12</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">A pimple or skin blemish</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">ZOO</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">12</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">A place where animals are kept</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">ZEE</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">12</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">The letter Z (American pronunciation)</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-medium text-gray-200 mt-6 mb-3">Z at the End</h3>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose my-4">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <thead class="bg-gray-800">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Word</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Points</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Meaning</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-800">
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">FEZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">15</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">A brimless conical red hat</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">WIZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">15</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">A wizard; an expert</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">FIZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">15</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">To make a hissing sound</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">BIZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">14</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Informal for business</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">COZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">14</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Informal for cousin</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">ADZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">13</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">A tool for shaping wood</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-medium text-gray-200 mt-6 mb-3">Z in the Middle</h3>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose my-4">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <thead class="bg-gray-800">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Word</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Points</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Meaning</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-800">
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300 font-bold">AZO</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">12</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Containing nitrogen (chemistry term)</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Z Placement Strategy on Premium Squares</h2>
      <p>Z is worth 10 points — the maximum tile value in Scrabble. Placing it on premium squares turns a good play into a game-changing one. Here's how to maximise your Z tile:</p>

      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Z on Triple Letter Score (TLS):</strong> Z becomes 30 points. This single tile contributes more than most entire words. ZAX with Z on TLS = 39 points total.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Z on Double Letter Score (DLS):</strong> Z becomes 20 points. Still excellent — FEZ with Z on DLS = 25 points.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Z word on Triple Word Score (TWS):</strong> The entire word is tripled. ZAX on TWS = 57 points. FEZ on TWS = 45 points.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Z word on Double Word Score (DWS):</strong> The entire word is doubled. ZAX on DWS = 38 points.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Position-Based Strategy</h2>
      <p>Having Z words for every position (beginning, middle, end) gives you flexibility to hit premium squares regardless of board layout:</p>

      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Z-first words (ZAP, ZAX, ZIT):</strong> Best when a premium square is available at the start of a row or above an existing word. You place Z on the premium square and build right.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Z-last words (FEZ, BIZ, ADZ):</strong> Best when a premium square is at the end of a row. Build left and land Z on the multiplier as your final tile.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Z-middle words (AZO):</strong> Useful when a premium square sits between two placed tiles. Less common but valuable for specific board states.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Hooking with Z Words</h2>
      <p>Many Z words can be extended, creating opportunities for future turns or allowing you to build off existing plays:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>ZAP → ZAPS, ZAPPED, ZAPPING:</strong> The most extensible Z word</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>ZIT → ZITS:</strong> Simple S hook</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>ZIG → ZIGS, ZIGGED, ZIGGING:</strong> Multiple extensions</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>ZAG → ZAGS, ZAGGED, ZAGGING:</strong> Same pattern as ZIG</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>ZOO → ZOOS, ZOOM:</strong> Extends with common tiles</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>ADZ → ADZE:</strong> Add E for the alternate spelling</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Z vs Q: Which Is Better?</h2>
      <p>Both Z and Q are worth 10 points, but Z is widely considered the better tile for several reasons:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>More word options:</strong> Z has 20+ valid 3-letter words; Q has only 4.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Common companions:</strong> Z pairs with A, I, E, O — all abundant tiles. Q typically needs U (scarce) or specific rare combinations.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Position flexibility:</strong> Z works at the start, middle, or end of words. Q almost always appears at the start.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Higher ceiling:</strong> ZAX (19) beats every Q word's base score (max 12). Combined with premium squares, Z words reach 57 points.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Quick Memorisation Tips</h2>
      <p>Group your Z words by the companion vowel you need:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Z + A:</strong> ZAX, ZAP, ZAG (the "ZA" family — A is the most common tile)</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Z + E:</strong> ZEP, ZEK, ZED, ZEE, FEZ (the "ZE" family)</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Z + I:</strong> ZIT, ZIG, BIZ, WIZ, FIZ (the "ZI" family)</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Z + O:</strong> ZOO, AZO, COZ (the "ZO" family)</span></li>
      </ul>
      <p>Since A, E, I, and O are the four most common vowels, you'll almost always have at least one Z word available when you draw the Z tile.</p>

      <!-- Related Articles -->
      <aside class="border-t border-gray-800 mt-12 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Related Articles</h3>
        <div class="grid gap-3">
          <a href="/blog/three-letter-words-with-q/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
